This book reassesses foreign policy in the Diefenbaker era to determine whether its failures can be mainly attributed to the prime minister’s personality traits, particularly his indecisiveness, or to broader shifts in world affairs. Written by leading scholars who mine new sources of archival research, the chapters examine the full range of international issues that confronted Diefenbaker and his ministers and probe the factors that led to success or failure, decision or indecision, on specific issues. Rather than dismissing Diefenbaker as a “Rogue Tory” on the world stage, this fascinating reconsideration of the Diefenbaker years challenges readers to push beyond the conventional and reassess his record with fresh eyes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aCampbell, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell-Miller, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarroll, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavell, Janice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavell, Janice, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDonaghy, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHillmer, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarion, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKenzie, Francine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKercher, Asa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNazzi, Stephe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSegal, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpooner, Kevin A., eco